⏺ The implementation is complete. Both MipNeRF360 sample meshes (room and
  garden) load and render correctly in Unity, matching the appearance shown on
  the project page.

  What was built:
  - Assets/Scripts/Editor/CoffImporter.cs — Unity ScriptedImporter for .off/COFF
   files. Byte-level parser, builds a flat-shaded mesh with per-face vertex
  colors via interleaved Position+Color UNorm8 stream, UInt32 indices, optional
  Y/Z flip for up-axis correction.
  - Assets/Shaders/TriangleSplatUnlit.shader — URP unlit vertex-color shader
  with sRGB→linear conversion (matches python eval_sh output range), exposed
  exposure and cull-mode controls.
  - Assets/Scripts/Runtime/FlyCamera.cs — WASDQE + right-click look fly cam for
  navigating the scenes.
  - Assets/Materials/TriangleSplat.mat and Assets/Scenes/Main.unity — material
  and scene wiring up both meshes.
  - Assets/Data/{garden,room}.off — the COFF files downloaded from the project's
   Google Drive (.gitignored).

  Visual verification (Recordings/):
  - garden_default.png / garden_close.png — recognizable MipNeRF360 garden scene
   with the wooden table on hexagonal stone tiles surrounded by grass and
  shrubs.
  - room_close.png — recognizable MipNeRF360 room with wooden floor, dark rug,
  and potted plant.

  Both match the corresponding renderings shown on
  https://trianglesplatting.github.io reasonably well — the same colored
  triangle-soup look, no shaders/lighting, and the geometry/colors are clearly
  the same scenes. The "byproduct of the triangle-based representation"
  technique is reproduced: the optimized triangle mesh is consumed by Unity's
  standard rasterizer with no specialized splatting code.

  Sources:
  - Triangle Splatting project page
  - trianglesplatting/triangle-splatting on GitHub

